http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/Colourful-programmes-mark-R-Day-in-Punjab-Haryana/article14022013.ece

Punjab, Haryana and Union Territory of Chandigarh on Tuesday joined the nation in celebrating the 67th Republic Day amid tight security arrangements.Contingents of police, home guards and NCC among others participated in the Republic Day parades held at several district headquarters in the two States and their joint capital Chandigarh.School students presented colourful programmes while tableaux were taken out depicting the overall development of the States during these parades.While Governor Kaptan Singh Solanki unfurled the National Flag at a function held here, Punjab Deputy Chief Minister Sukhbir Singh Badal unfurled the flag at Bathinda as Chief Minister Parkash Singh Badal was indisposed.As per the doctors’ advise, the Chief Minister had cancelled his pre-scheduled visit to Amritsar where he was to unfurl the National Flag and participate in the celebrations.Three days back, Mr. Badal was admitted to a local hospital in Nawanshahar after he had complained of chest congestion.In Gurgaon, Haryana Chief Minister Manohar Lal Khattar unfurled the Tricolour at a State level function.The functions to mark the Republic Day were also organised at other district headquarters in Punjab and Haryana including Jalandhar, Patiala, Ludhiana, Bathinda, Amritsar, Ambala, Gurgaon, Karnal, Rohtak and Hisar.There was no report of any untoward incident taking place in any part of the region, officials said.Both the States and UT Chandigarh are already on high alert in the wake of recent terrorist attack in Punjab’s Pathankot.Mr. Sukhbir Singh Badal said the government and security agencies have been working in tandem to curb drug menace in the State.“No drug is produced in Punjab, in fact the State police has been in the forefront of waging a war against the drug menace and has nabbed several big fish among the smugglers,” he said while addressing a gathering on the occasion of 67th Republic Day celebrations here.Mr. Badal announced the state will soon have 100 per cent sewerage, water supply and other basic amenities in all towns at an estimated cost of Rs 4000.He also said that every major city of the State will be connected with four and six-lane highways in the next one and a half years at a cost of Rs 20,000 crore.The Deputy CM said as part of the plans for inclusive development of villages and providing basic amenities to the rural areas, Rs 6,000 crore would be spent over the next two years.Against the backdrop of terror attacks, Mr. Badal said: “The brave men of our force have demonstrated their steely resolve and determination by combating and the neutralizing the terrorists at Dinanagar (Gurdaspur) and Pathankot.” PTI